  "prompt": "How do you sort a collection in Java?",
  "response": "In Java, there are several ways to sort collections:\n\n1. Using Collections.sort() for Lists:\n```java\n// For a list of comparable objects\nList<Integer> numbers = Arrays.asList(5, 2, 8, 1, 9);\nCollections.sort(numbers);\n\n// For descending order\nCollections.sort(numbers, Collections.reverseOrder());\n```\n\n2. Using List.sort() method (Java 8+):\n```java\nList<String> names = Arrays.asList(\"Alice\", \"Bob\", \"Charlie\");\nnames.sort(null); // natural ordering\nnames.sort(Comparator.naturalOrder());\nnames.sort(Comparator.reverseOrder());\n```\n\n3. Custom Comparator:\n```java\nList<Person> people = new ArrayList<>();\n// Sort by age\npeople.sort(Comparator.comparing(Person::getAge));\n\n// Sort by multiple criteria\npeople.sort(Comparator.comparing(Person::getLastName)\n                      .thenComparing(Person::getFirstName));\n\n// Reverse order\npeople.sort(Comparator.comparing(Person::getAge).reversed());\n```\n\n4. For Arrays:\n```java\nint[] numbers = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9};\nArrays.sort(numbers);\n\n// For object arrays\nPerson[] peopleArray = new Person[]{...};\nArrays.sort(peopleArray, Comparator.comparing(Person::getAge));\n```\n\n5. TreeSet (automatic sorting):\n```java\n// Automatically sorts elements\nTreeSet<Integer> sortedSet = new TreeSet<>();\nsortedSet.addAll(Arrays.asList(5, 2, 8, 1, 9));\n```\n\n6. Creating a Custom Comparator:\n```java\nComparator<Person> customComparator = new Comparator<Person>() {\n    @Override\n    public int compare(Person p1, Person p2) {\n        return p1.getAge() - p2.getAge();\n    }\n};\n\n// Or using lambda (Java 8+)\nComparator<Person> customComparator = (p1, p2) -> p1.getAge() - p2.getAge();\n\npeople.sort(customComparator);\n```\n\nKey Points:\n- `Collections.sort()` works only for Lists\n- `Arrays.sort()` works for arrays\n- For custom sorting, use Comparator\n- Java 8+ introduces more concise sorting methods\n- Natural ordering requires the class to implement Comparable\n- Custom sorting uses Comparator\n\nExample with a complete class:\n```java\nclass Person implements Comparable<Person> {\n    private String name;\n    private int age;\n\n    // Constructor, getters, etc.\n\n    @Override\n    public int compareTo(Person other) {\n        return Integer.compare(this.age, other.age);\n    }\n}\n\n// Usage\nList<Person> people = new ArrayList<>();\n// Add people\nCollections.sort(people); // uses natural ordering\n```\n\nChoose the method that best fits your specific use case and Java version.",
